1
00:00:00,031 --> 00:00:02,159
At T plus zero point six seven eight seconds,

2
00:00:02,159 --> 00:00:04,878
the first warning appeared.

3
00:00:05,580 --> 00:00:08,699
It was smoke from the aft field joint of Challenger's

4
00:00:08,699 --> 00:00:10,367
right solid rocket booster.

5
00:00:11,307 --> 00:00:13,536
More smoke followed through the first two and a half

6
00:00:13,536 --> 00:00:15,916
seconds of flight. Then it stopped.

7
00:00:16,876 --> 00:00:19,501
For the next minute, Challenger looked like a launch.

8
00:00:20,181 --> 00:00:22,905
The vehicle climbed. The callouts continued.

9
00:00:23,527 --> 00:00:26,322
The machinery of the mission appeared to be doing what

10
00:00:26,322 --> 00:00:27,253
it had done before.

11
00:00:27,253 --> 00:00:29,036
But the accident had already begun.

12
00:00:29,076 --> 00:00:32,210
The visible catastrophe came later,

13
00:00:32,210 --> 00:00:34,926
about seventy-three seconds after liftoff.

14
00:00:34,945 --> 00:00:37,109
By then the public version could be told quickly:

15
00:00:37,149 --> 00:00:40,023
it was cold, the O-rings failed,

16
00:00:40,023 --> 00:00:42,298
and seven crew members died.

17
00:00:43,039 --> 00:00:44,802
That version is accurate.

18
00:00:44,802 --> 00:00:47,248
It is also too small to explain why launch was

19
00:00:47,248 --> 00:00:51,180
still allowed. The smoke is the better starting point because

20
00:00:51,180 --> 00:00:53,295
it separates the consequence from the beginning.

21
00:00:54,195 --> 00:00:56,579
At seventy-three seconds, the chain became public.

22
00:00:57,301 --> 00:00:58,593
At less than one second,

23
00:00:58,593 --> 00:01:00,265
the chain became physical.

24
00:01:01,045 --> 00:01:03,990
Before that, the chain had already been organizational.

25
00:01:03,990 --> 00:01:06,091
The harder question starts before ignition:

26
00:01:06,772 --> 00:01:09,905
how does a warning stay visible in records,

27
00:01:09,905 --> 00:01:12,859
inspections, memos, charts, and meetings,

28
00:01:12,859 --> 00:01:16,529
then arrive at the final decision too weak to stop

29
00:01:16,529 --> 00:01:20,653
the machine? Challenger did not fail because the danger was

30
00:01:20,653 --> 00:01:23,983
invisible. It failed after a system learned how to keep

31
00:01:23,983 --> 00:01:26,832
flying with evidence that should have made flying harder.

32
00:01:27,733 --> 00:01:29,607
To understand how that happens,

33
00:01:29,607 --> 00:01:32,778
start with the promise the Shuttle system had to keep.

34
00:01:32,778 --> 00:01:36,165
Mercury, Gemini, and Apollo were built around singular missions.

35
00:01:37,027 --> 00:01:39,813
Dedicated hardware. Dedicated risk.

36
00:01:40,573 --> 00:01:44,784
Dedicated public attention. The Shuttle was designed to break that

37
00:01:44,784 --> 00:01:48,611
model. Reusable. Frequent. Routine.

38
00:01:48,611 --> 00:01:51,575
Less expedition, more airline.

39
00:01:52,376 --> 00:01:54,902
That promise shaped the organization around it.

40
00:01:55,590 --> 00:01:57,463
When a program promises routine,

41
00:01:57,463 --> 00:02:00,239
every delay starts to mean something different.

42
00:02:01,102 --> 00:02:04,128
A scrub is still an engineering decision,

43
00:02:04,128 --> 00:02:06,531
but it is also a schedule problem.

44
00:02:06,531 --> 00:02:09,023
A budget problem. A public problem.

45
00:02:09,023 --> 00:02:11,961
A problem that moves through contracts,

46
00:02:11,961 --> 00:02:17,301
payload windows, congressional expectations, and the reputation of the

47
00:02:17,301 --> 00:02:21,811
agency. NASA entered 1986 with an aggressive flight schedule and

48
00:02:21,811 --> 00:02:25,641
a system that had to justify itself through repetition.

49
00:02:26,562 --> 00:02:28,830
The Shuttle was not only a spacecraft.

50
00:02:28,830 --> 00:02:30,366
It was an operating model.

51
00:02:31,227 --> 00:02:34,514
The first thing to understand about Challenger is that the

52
00:02:34,514 --> 00:02:37,332
program was built to make spaceflight feel normal.

53
00:02:38,293 --> 00:02:39,935
Normal operation is useful.

54
00:02:40,675 --> 00:02:43,765
It is also dangerous when it teaches people to treat

55
00:02:43,765 --> 00:02:46,640
unresolved problems as background conditions.

56
00:02:47,092 --> 00:02:49,611
No one in this story needed to wake up wanting

57
00:02:49,611 --> 00:02:53,218
a disaster. That matters because the easy version turns the

58
00:02:53,218 --> 00:02:55,030
accident into a morality play.

59
00:02:55,890 --> 00:02:57,366
Bad people made bad choices,

60
00:02:57,366 --> 00:02:59,419
so better people would have stopped it.

61
00:03:00,341 --> 00:03:02,384
The record is harder than that.

62
00:03:02,669 --> 00:03:05,267
The system was full of people trying to do their

63
00:03:05,267 --> 00:03:08,730
jobs inside a decision structure that kept lowering the force

64
00:03:08,730 --> 00:03:12,381
of warnings. Three pressures were running at the same time.

65
00:03:13,301 --> 00:03:18,407
First: technical uncertainty. The Shuttle was enormously complex.

66
00:03:19,109 --> 00:03:23,377
Each flight produced new evidence about how hardware behaved in

67
00:03:23,377 --> 00:03:25,590
the real vehicle, under real loads,

68
00:03:25,590 --> 00:03:29,300
in real weather. That gap between design expectation and operating

69
00:03:29,300 --> 00:03:31,122
evidence is normal in engineering.

70
00:03:31,824 --> 00:03:33,945
What matters is how the gap gets handled.

71
00:03:35,007 --> 00:03:39,809
Second: schedule pressure. Delays did not move one item on

72
00:03:39,809 --> 00:03:42,985
one calendar. They shifted payloads,

73
00:03:42,985 --> 00:03:46,139
crews, customers, reviews, and promises.

74
00:03:46,979 --> 00:03:49,481
The cost of stopping was visible immediately.

75
00:03:50,603 --> 00:03:55,806
Third: institutional reputation. NASA was not only an engineering

76
00:03:55,806 --> 00:03:58,981
organization. It was a national symbol,

77
00:03:58,981 --> 00:04:01,514
a funding case, a Cold War instrument,

78
00:04:01,514 --> 00:04:02,780
and a public trust.

79
00:04:03,600 --> 00:04:06,145
These pressures met inside the same rooms.

80
00:04:06,866 --> 00:04:11,252
When they conflicted, the most flexible thing was often uncertainty.

81
00:04:11,252 --> 00:04:13,394
A technical concern could be reframed.

82
00:04:14,074 --> 00:04:15,036
It could be qualified.

83
00:04:15,736 --> 00:04:17,418
It could be moved to the next review.

84
00:04:18,119 --> 00:04:20,422
Schedule and reputation were harder to bend.

85
00:04:21,281 --> 00:04:23,043
So the practical standard drifted.

86
00:04:23,064 --> 00:04:27,853
The question became: keep flying unless the evidence against flying

87
00:04:27,853 --> 00:04:31,838
is overwhelming. That is very different from:

88
00:04:31,838 --> 00:04:35,416
do not fly unless the evidence for safety is clear.

89
00:04:35,416 --> 00:04:38,021
The difference showed up most clearly in one component.

90
00:04:38,903 --> 00:04:41,735
The Shuttle used two solid rocket boosters for most of

91
00:04:41,735 --> 00:04:44,315
its thrust during the first two minutes of flight.

92
00:04:45,257 --> 00:04:48,764
Each booster was not built as one continuous piece.

93
00:04:48,785 --> 00:04:51,740
It was assembled from cylindrical segments,

94
00:04:51,740 --> 00:04:54,216
stacked and joined at the launch site.

95
00:04:54,216 --> 00:04:56,939
Where the segments met, there was a field joint.

96
00:04:57,720 --> 00:05:00,298
Inside that joint, two rubber O-rings,

97
00:05:00,298 --> 00:05:02,103
a primary and a secondary,

98
00:05:02,103 --> 00:05:05,885
were supposed to seal the gap and keep hot combustion

99
00:05:05,885 --> 00:05:07,690
gases inside the booster.

100
00:05:08,552 --> 00:05:10,074
The joint had to seal quickly.

101
00:05:10,774 --> 00:05:13,512
Pressure inside the motor could distort the metal parts at

102
00:05:13,512 --> 00:05:17,566
ignition. The O-rings had to move into position fast enough

103
00:05:17,566 --> 00:05:19,545
to block hot gas before it escaped.

104
00:05:20,031 --> 00:05:22,795
Cold mattered because rubber does not respond the same way

105
00:05:22,795 --> 00:05:26,137
in cold. A seal that moves quickly when warm can

106
00:05:26,137 --> 00:05:27,778
respond more slowly when cold.

107
00:05:28,540 --> 00:05:31,523
In this joint, timing was not a detail.

108
00:05:32,324 --> 00:05:34,425
Timing was the safety margin.

109
00:05:35,245 --> 00:05:38,608
If the seals failed, there was no graceful backup.

110
00:05:39,290 --> 00:05:42,133
Hot gas could burn through the booster casing,

111
00:05:42,133 --> 00:05:45,650
reach surrounding structure, and turn a local leak into a

112
00:05:45,650 --> 00:05:49,383
vehicle failure. The O-ring problem had been showing itself before

113
00:05:49,383 --> 00:05:53,853
Challenger. Post-flight inspections found erosion on the primary seal.

114
00:05:54,634 --> 00:05:57,118
In some cases, gas had blown past it and left

115
00:05:57,118 --> 00:05:58,821
evidence deeper in the joint.

116
00:05:59,822 --> 00:06:01,423
Engineers documented the damage.

117
00:06:02,045 --> 00:06:04,067
They measured it. They reported it.

118
00:06:04,869 --> 00:06:07,351
The dangerous part is what happened next.

119
00:06:07,702 --> 00:06:11,693
Because the missions succeeded, because the vehicles came home,

120
00:06:11,693 --> 00:06:15,376
damage could be processed as evidence that the system had

121
00:06:15,376 --> 00:06:20,260
tolerated the condition. A damaged component in a surviving system

122
00:06:20,260 --> 00:06:21,279
can be read two ways.

123
00:06:22,262 --> 00:06:25,484
One reading says: we were closer to failure than we

124
00:06:25,484 --> 00:06:28,178
should have been, so we stop and fix the condition

125
00:06:28,178 --> 00:06:29,255
before we repeat it.

126
00:06:30,057 --> 00:06:32,595
The other says: the vehicle survived,

127
00:06:32,595 --> 00:06:35,979
the margin held, and the risk can be carried while

128
00:06:35,979 --> 00:06:40,998
improvement work continues. The second reading became easier each time

129
00:06:40,998 --> 00:06:42,377
the Shuttle flew and returned.

130
00:06:43,057 --> 00:06:46,908
What had started as a serious anomaly gradually became part

131
00:06:46,908 --> 00:06:48,526
of the operating history.

132
00:06:48,526 --> 00:06:50,488
The O-ring warning did not disappear.

133
00:06:51,309 --> 00:06:54,386
It moved. That is how a warning can die inside

134
00:06:54,386 --> 00:06:58,095
a large organization. Not through silence.

135
00:06:58,115 --> 00:07:02,718
Through translation. It starts when an engineer sees something wrong.

136
00:07:03,459 --> 00:07:04,860
The data is specific.

137
00:07:05,442 --> 00:07:06,762
The language is uncomfortable.

138
00:07:07,382 --> 00:07:10,146
Erosion. Blow-by. Heat effects.

139
00:07:10,865 --> 00:07:13,229
A seal that did not behave the way the design

140
00:07:13,229 --> 00:07:17,232
assumed. Precise evidence has force.

141
00:07:17,232 --> 00:07:19,475
Then the evidence becomes a discussion item.

142
00:07:20,177 --> 00:07:23,654
It enters a meeting with dozens of other concerns.

143
00:07:23,654 --> 00:07:25,860
Other anomalies. Other systems.

144
00:07:25,860 --> 00:07:31,153
Other deadlines. The context broadens and the urgency flattens.

145
00:07:31,793 --> 00:07:34,678
From there, the discussion becomes a judgment call.

146
00:07:35,420 --> 00:07:37,583
Does this affect the next flight?

147
00:07:37,583 --> 00:07:40,492
The answer depends on the question the room decides to

148
00:07:40,492 --> 00:07:42,508
ask. If the question is,

149
00:07:42,508 --> 00:07:44,654
can we prove this will cause a failure,

150
00:07:45,295 --> 00:07:46,517
the answer is usually no.

151
00:07:47,379 --> 00:07:50,425
Predicting a specific loss on a specific flight is hard.

152
00:07:51,206 --> 00:07:53,892
If the question is, can we prove this will not

153
00:07:53,892 --> 00:07:55,973
fail, the answer is also no.

154
00:07:56,754 --> 00:07:59,019
But the first question keeps the schedule alive.

155
00:07:59,961 --> 00:08:02,625
Then the judgment becomes a schedule decision.

156
00:08:02,625 --> 00:08:04,146
The language changes again.

157
00:08:04,166 --> 00:08:08,020
It is no longer mainly about erosion depth or sealing

158
00:08:08,020 --> 00:08:11,226
time. It is about whether there is enough cause to

159
00:08:11,226 --> 00:08:13,757
delay. Delay has a phone tree.

160
00:08:14,437 --> 00:08:17,480
Delay has cost. Delay has a visible owner.

161
00:08:18,482 --> 00:08:22,005
If the flight succeeds, the decision becomes precedent.

162
00:08:22,786 --> 00:08:24,709
We flew with that condition and came back.

163
00:08:25,670 --> 00:08:28,689
That fact starts to compete with the warning that preceded

164
00:08:28,689 --> 00:08:32,476
it. This route ran more than once before Challenger.

165
00:08:32,476 --> 00:08:35,119
Each pass made the next one easier to defend.

166
00:08:35,919 --> 00:08:37,856
Engineers were not simply ignored.

167
00:08:37,856 --> 00:08:40,928
They were often heard, then absorbed into a process that

168
00:08:40,928 --> 00:08:44,067
had learned how to carry their concern without stopping.

169
00:08:45,008 --> 00:08:48,893
Months before Challenger, Roger Boisjoly warned that a similar

170
00:08:48,893 --> 00:08:52,921
field-joint problem could lead to catastrophe of the highest order

171
00:08:52,921 --> 00:08:54,216
and loss of human life.

172
00:08:55,317 --> 00:08:57,480
That memo did not come from hindsight.

173
00:08:58,320 --> 00:09:00,787
It came from inside the system,

174
00:09:00,787 --> 00:09:04,586
before the accident, from an engineer close to the hardware.

175
00:09:05,508 --> 00:09:08,463
The temperature pattern also had more weight than the launch-night

176
00:09:08,463 --> 00:09:09,413
argument made it feel.

177
00:09:10,215 --> 00:09:12,784
When the full flight history was framed one way,

178
00:09:12,784 --> 00:09:15,422
the cold-weather signal could look debatable.

179
00:09:16,484 --> 00:09:19,553
When the full record was framed another way,

180
00:09:19,553 --> 00:09:23,133
cold O-ring distress became much harder to dismiss.

181
00:09:24,014 --> 00:09:27,823
A chart can contain real information and still weaken the

182
00:09:27,823 --> 00:09:30,442
warning if it frames the wrong question.

183
00:09:30,642 --> 00:09:34,169
Richard Feynman's later appendix named the broader danger plainly:

184
00:09:34,932 --> 00:09:37,518
previous success can become misleading evidence.

185
00:09:38,399 --> 00:09:40,784
A survived flight can show that the vehicle got through.

186
00:09:40,825 --> 00:09:43,912
It does not prove the risk was safe to repeat.

187
00:09:45,174 --> 00:09:49,865
By January 1986, Challenger was not facing a new problem.

188
00:09:49,947 --> 00:09:52,090
The program had evidence of O-ring distress.

189
00:09:52,789 --> 00:09:53,991
It had temperature concern.

190
00:09:54,633 --> 00:09:56,674
It had waivers. It had memos.

191
00:09:57,255 --> 00:09:59,118
It had a known field-joint problem.

192
00:09:59,778 --> 00:10:02,982
It had a launch system that kept treating survival as

193
00:10:02,982 --> 00:10:04,365
part of the safety case.

194
00:10:04,384 --> 00:10:06,850
Then the weather turned that old problem into a launch

195
00:10:06,850 --> 00:10:10,932
decision. January 27, 1986.

196
00:10:11,994 --> 00:10:15,177
Less than twenty-four hours before the scheduled launch.

197
00:10:15,177 --> 00:10:19,206
A teleconference connected NASA's Marshall Space Flight Center,

198
00:10:19,206 --> 00:10:21,755
Kennedy Space Center, and Morton Thiokol,

199
00:10:21,755 --> 00:10:25,053
the contractor that built the solid rocket boosters.

200
00:10:25,975 --> 00:10:28,078
The subject was temperature.

201
00:10:29,039 --> 00:10:33,128
Forecasts and engineering estimates pointed to launch conditions far

202
00:10:33,128 --> 00:10:35,309
colder than prior Shuttle experience.

203
00:10:35,309 --> 00:10:38,615
The launch temperature would be about 36 degrees Fahrenheit.

204
00:10:39,557 --> 00:10:42,776
The right aft field joint was estimated colder,

205
00:10:42,776 --> 00:10:46,407
around 28 degrees Fahrenheit, plus or minus five degrees.

206
00:10:46,407 --> 00:10:51,327
Thiokol engineers were concerned because cold could slow the O-rings

207
00:10:51,327 --> 00:10:53,518
at the exact moment they needed to seal.

208
00:10:53,903 --> 00:10:58,280
Their recommendation was clear: do not launch below 53 degrees

209
00:10:58,280 --> 00:11:02,554
Fahrenheit. That number mattered because it was tied to the

210
00:11:02,554 --> 00:11:06,028
lowest relevant prior experience they believed they could defend.

211
00:11:07,130 --> 00:11:08,614
NASA managers pushed back.

212
00:11:09,336 --> 00:11:12,822
In a technical review, pushback can be necessary.

213
00:11:13,106 --> 00:11:15,526
The danger was the standard that began to govern the

214
00:11:15,526 --> 00:11:17,674
room. The question drifted.

215
00:11:18,677 --> 00:11:22,371
Show that this is safe to fly became prove that

216
00:11:22,371 --> 00:11:26,250
it will fail. That shift reversed the burden of proof.

217
00:11:27,231 --> 00:11:30,170
Instead of requiring evidence that launch was safe,

218
00:11:30,170 --> 00:11:33,383
the process demanded evidence that failure was certain.

219
00:11:34,384 --> 00:11:37,629
Engineering evidence usually does not arrive that way.

220
00:11:37,629 --> 00:11:39,585
It arrives as a missing margin,

221
00:11:39,585 --> 00:11:43,613
a condition outside experience, a trend with enough signal to

222
00:11:43,613 --> 00:11:47,010
matter before the catastrophe supplies certainty.

223
00:11:47,051 --> 00:11:50,197
The engineers had evidence of risk.

224
00:11:50,217 --> 00:11:52,900
They did not have an equation that converted temperature into

225
00:11:52,900 --> 00:11:54,086
guaranteed loss of vehicle.

226
00:11:54,727 --> 00:11:57,693
That absence became useful to the launch case.

227
00:11:57,693 --> 00:11:59,937
Thiokol asked for an offline caucus.

228
00:12:00,677 --> 00:12:03,518
The caucus lasted far longer than the five minutes first

229
00:12:03,518 --> 00:12:07,466
requested. When they returned, the recommendation had changed.

230
00:12:08,206 --> 00:12:10,725
The new position was that the data was inconclusive and

231
00:12:10,725 --> 00:12:13,874
launch could proceed. The cold had not changed.

232
00:12:14,433 --> 00:12:16,155
The joint had not changed.

233
00:12:16,797 --> 00:12:18,599
The limits of the data had not changed.

234
00:12:19,259 --> 00:12:20,682
The decision frame changed.

235
00:12:21,582 --> 00:12:25,140
One instruction from that caucus still carries the shape of

236
00:12:25,140 --> 00:12:28,329
the moment. Jerry Mason told Bob Lund to take off

237
00:12:28,329 --> 00:12:31,225
his engineering hat and put on his management hat.

238
00:12:32,048 --> 00:12:34,035
No single phrase explains the disaster.

239
00:12:34,096 --> 00:12:36,945
No single person explains it either.

240
00:12:37,465 --> 00:12:40,528
The deeper fact is that the same process could take

241
00:12:40,528 --> 00:12:45,122
a specific engineering objection and return a launch recommendation from

242
00:12:45,122 --> 00:12:49,039
the same evidence. The launch-eve reversal is dramatic,

243
00:12:49,039 --> 00:12:50,823
but it is not the whole failure.

244
00:12:51,585 --> 00:12:54,248
A warning also has to travel.

245
00:12:54,969 --> 00:12:57,925
It has to move from hardware to engineers,

246
00:12:57,925 --> 00:13:01,750
from engineers to managers, from contractors to NASA,

247
00:13:01,750 --> 00:13:05,836
from lower review levels to the people with authority to

248
00:13:05,836 --> 00:13:07,711
stop the launch. At each step,

249
00:13:07,711 --> 00:13:09,548
the signal can be compressed.

250
00:13:10,408 --> 00:13:12,899
Compression is normal in large programs.

251
00:13:12,899 --> 00:13:16,928
But when compression changes an active objection into a resolved

252
00:13:16,928 --> 00:13:20,152
item, the system has made a decision without naming it

253
00:13:20,152 --> 00:13:23,140
directly. Safety should have been a backstop.

254
00:13:23,860 --> 00:13:27,351
The Commission later criticized weak problem reporting,

255
00:13:27,351 --> 00:13:30,842
inadequate trend analysis, misrepresented criticality,

256
00:13:30,842 --> 00:13:34,406
and safety structures that did not give the concern enough

257
00:13:34,406 --> 00:13:36,952
independent force at the decisive points.

258
00:13:36,952 --> 00:13:41,064
People can care about safety while the way decisions are

259
00:13:41,064 --> 00:13:44,054
made still lets a warning arrive too late,

260
00:13:44,054 --> 00:13:47,043
too thin, or too resolved to change action.

261
00:13:48,125 --> 00:13:53,593
By launch morning, the warning had passed through hardware evidence,

262
00:13:53,593 --> 00:13:57,815
paperwork, meetings, waivers, charts, recommendation,

263
00:13:57,815 --> 00:14:00,597
caucus, and management acceptance.

264
00:14:00,618 --> 00:14:02,253
At the end of that route,

265
00:14:02,253 --> 00:14:03,801
launch was still open.

266
00:14:04,101 --> 00:14:10,173
At 11:38 a.m. Eastern Standard Time on January 28,

267
00:14:10,173 --> 00:14:14,634
1986, Challenger launched from Kennedy Space Center.

268
00:14:15,289 --> 00:14:18,836
Within the first second, smoke appeared near the right aft

269
00:14:18,836 --> 00:14:22,417
field joint. The primary O-ring had not sealed the way

270
00:14:22,417 --> 00:14:23,318
it needed to seal.

271
00:14:24,120 --> 00:14:27,779
The secondary O-ring, affected by cold and joint movement,

272
00:14:27,779 --> 00:14:29,725
had not saved the joint in time.

273
00:14:30,586 --> 00:14:33,185
The smoke continued through roughly T plus two and a

274
00:14:33,185 --> 00:14:35,491
half seconds. Then it disappeared.

275
00:14:36,332 --> 00:14:40,153
The Commission considered that combustion residue may have temporarily

276
00:14:40,153 --> 00:14:42,117
sealed the breach. For a short time,

277
00:14:42,117 --> 00:14:45,749
the vehicle could look normal while the failure chain remained

278
00:14:45,749 --> 00:14:50,246
alive. That temporary quiet is one of the clearest details

279
00:14:50,246 --> 00:14:54,337
in the record. The physical system did what the organization

280
00:14:54,337 --> 00:14:55,484
had been doing for years:

281
00:14:56,325 --> 00:14:58,327
a sign of breach appeared,

282
00:14:58,327 --> 00:15:01,951
an explanation arrived, and flight continued.

283
00:15:01,951 --> 00:15:04,579
Around 58 to 59 seconds into flight,

284
00:15:04,579 --> 00:15:06,678
flame became visible again.

285
00:15:06,698 --> 00:15:11,184
Hot gas from the right booster began damaging surrounding structure,

286
00:15:11,184 --> 00:15:13,349
including the External Tank area.

287
00:15:14,309 --> 00:15:17,916
At approximately seventy-three seconds, Challenger broke apart.

288
00:15:18,876 --> 00:15:22,188
Francis "Dick" Scobee, Michael Smith,

289
00:15:22,188 --> 00:15:26,641
Judith Resnik, Ellison Onizuka, Ronald McNair,

290
00:15:26,641 --> 00:15:31,095
Gregory Jarvis, and Christa McAuliffe were lost.

291
00:15:31,210 --> 00:15:33,332
The visible failure lasted seconds.

292
00:15:34,115 --> 00:15:36,578
The invisible one had been accumulating for years.

293
00:15:37,500 --> 00:15:40,785
What came next was the question every institution fears:

294
00:15:41,547 --> 00:15:44,091
how did this happen when the evidence already existed?

295
00:15:45,052 --> 00:15:47,889
President Reagan appointed the Rogers Commission,

296
00:15:47,889 --> 00:15:49,340
chaired by William Rogers.

297
00:15:50,380 --> 00:15:52,459
Richard Feynman was one of its members,

298
00:15:52,459 --> 00:15:55,785
and his independent work became part of the public memory

299
00:15:55,785 --> 00:15:59,181
of the investigation. The physical cause was direct:

300
00:15:59,903 --> 00:16:03,534
failure of the seal in the right booster's aft field

301
00:16:03,534 --> 00:16:07,511
joint, hot gas escaping, damage to the External Tank area,

302
00:16:07,511 --> 00:16:12,025
and vehicle breakup. The Commission did not stop at the

303
00:16:12,025 --> 00:16:15,833
physical cause. It found a flawed launch decision process.

304
00:16:16,595 --> 00:16:18,057
It found communication failures.

305
00:16:18,837 --> 00:16:22,275
It found that crucial information about O-ring history,

306
00:16:22,275 --> 00:16:26,983
temperature concern, and continuing engineering opposition did not reach

307
00:16:26,983 --> 00:16:30,495
key decision-makers with the force and clarity it needed.

308
00:16:30,514 --> 00:16:35,233
The people closest to the hardware had the sharpest version

309
00:16:35,233 --> 00:16:38,385
of the risk. The people with the authority to stop

310
00:16:38,385 --> 00:16:40,889
launch received a softened version of it.

311
00:16:40,889 --> 00:16:43,889
The Commission described the immediate failure:

312
00:16:43,889 --> 00:16:45,657
the part, the launch decision,

313
00:16:45,657 --> 00:16:49,118
and the communication system that softened the warning.

314
00:16:50,078 --> 00:16:52,920
Diane Vaughan later named the larger pattern:

315
00:16:52,920 --> 00:16:54,864
the normalization of deviance.

316
00:16:55,825 --> 00:16:59,595
A deviation from expected performance becomes normal because the system

317
00:16:59,595 --> 00:17:03,434
keeps surviving it. The phrase is useful because it does

318
00:17:03,434 --> 00:17:04,794
not require a conspiracy.

319
00:17:05,693 --> 00:17:09,357
It describes a slow adjustment in what feels acceptable.

320
00:17:09,727 --> 00:17:13,056
The line moves because each previous crossing did not end

321
00:17:13,056 --> 00:17:17,933
in catastrophe. Challenger is taught in engineering programs,

322
00:17:17,933 --> 00:17:22,306
business schools, and organizational behavior courses because the

323
00:17:22,306 --> 00:17:24,224
pattern is not limited to NASA.

324
00:17:24,458 --> 00:17:28,082
Repeated near-misses create false confidence.

325
00:17:28,102 --> 00:17:31,329
Every time a system survives a close call,

326
00:17:31,329 --> 00:17:33,228
perceived risk can drop.

327
00:17:33,969 --> 00:17:37,132
The near-miss gets counted as validation instead of warning.

328
00:17:37,893 --> 00:17:39,954
Missing data gets mistaken for safety.

329
00:17:40,836 --> 00:17:43,743
No evidence of failure is not the same as evidence

330
00:17:43,743 --> 00:17:47,430
of no failure, especially when the dangerous condition has not

331
00:17:47,430 --> 00:17:53,250
really been tested. Schedule pressure changes proof standards quietly.

332
00:17:53,250 --> 00:17:55,555
No one has to announce that the bar has moved.

333
00:17:56,215 --> 00:17:59,311
The bar for stopping can rise inch by inch until

334
00:17:59,311 --> 00:18:02,249
only certainty of disaster justifies delay.

335
00:18:03,372 --> 00:18:06,278
Institutions reward continuity over interruption.

336
00:18:07,237 --> 00:18:09,776
The person who keeps the line moving is easier to

337
00:18:09,776 --> 00:18:12,316
celebrate than the person who stops it for a risk

338
00:18:12,316 --> 00:18:14,030
that might never become visible.

339
00:18:15,032 --> 00:18:16,757
Anomalies become background noise.

340
00:18:17,538 --> 00:18:19,822
The first time something unexpected happens,

341
00:18:19,822 --> 00:18:22,713
it gets attention. The fifth time,

342
00:18:22,713 --> 00:18:25,734
a tracking number. The tenth time,

343
00:18:26,338 --> 00:18:28,604
it starts to sound like how the system works.

344
00:18:29,626 --> 00:18:33,672
These behaviors appear wherever the cost of stopping is immediate

345
00:18:33,672 --> 00:18:36,201
and the cost of continuing is statistical.

346
00:18:36,201 --> 00:18:40,799
Healthcare systems. Financial systems.

347
00:18:40,799 --> 00:18:45,933
Infrastructure. Software. Any organization that has to decide whether a

348
00:18:45,933 --> 00:18:48,707
warning is strong enough to interrupt momentum.

349
00:18:49,689 --> 00:18:51,551
Challenger did not invent this pattern.

350
00:18:52,313 --> 00:18:53,515
It made the pattern visible.

351
00:18:54,416 --> 00:18:56,921
Disasters rarely begin at the moment of impact.

352
00:18:57,662 --> 00:19:01,299
They begin when a system gets used to explaining away

353
00:19:01,299 --> 00:19:04,192
what it should have stopped to understand.

354
00:19:04,192 --> 00:19:06,779
Challenger was a long sequence of accommodations,

355
00:19:06,779 --> 00:19:09,323
each one easier to defend than the whole chain would

356
00:19:09,323 --> 00:19:12,163
have been. The smoke at T plus zero point six

357
00:19:12,163 --> 00:19:14,912
seven eight seconds is why the story should not start

358
00:19:14,912 --> 00:19:19,545
with the explosion. The first visible warning was small.

359
00:19:19,545 --> 00:19:22,383
Then it vanished. For a while,

360
00:19:22,383 --> 00:19:26,164
everything looked normal. The same thing had already happened inside

361
00:19:26,164 --> 00:19:28,630
the organization. A warning appeared.

362
00:19:29,452 --> 00:19:30,536
The system explained it.

363
00:19:31,218 --> 00:19:33,439
The launch continued. Next time,

364
00:19:33,439 --> 00:19:37,796
another design failure, another system that taught itself to ignore

365
00:19:37,796 --> 00:19:38,784
what it already knew.
